1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,200
Hello everyone and welcome back to another edition here at EnglishPod.
大家好，欢迎回到EnglishPod的另一期节目。

2
00:00:07,200 --> 00:00:08,200
My name is Marco.
我是Marco。

3
00:00:08,200 --> 00:00:11,920
And my name is Catherine and today we've got a great upper intermediate level lesson for
我是Catherine，今天我们为大家准备了一节很棒的中高级课程，主题是

4
00:00:11,920 --> 00:00:15,360
you all about animal and human rights.
动物权利和人类权利。

5
00:00:15,360 --> 00:00:16,360
Right.
没错。

6
00:00:16,360 --> 00:00:18,800
So it's a very debatable topic.
这是一个非常有争议的话题。

7
00:00:18,800 --> 00:00:22,480
People want to protect animals, mistreatment of animals.
人们想要保护动物，反对虐待动物。

8
00:00:22,480 --> 00:00:25,640
And this is what we're going to talk about today, protecting animals and giving them
这就是我们今天要讨论的内容——保护动物并赋予它们

9
00:00:25,640 --> 00:00:26,640
rights.
权利。

10
00:00:26,640 --> 00:00:27,640
Do you think animals have rights?
你觉得动物有权利吗？

11
00:00:27,640 --> 00:00:31,000
Eh, well, you know, I think we could leave that for the end.
嗯，这个嘛，我觉得我们可以把这个问题留到最后讨论。

12
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:35,480
I don't want to, you know, influence the argument here in today's dialogue.
我不想影响今天对话中的论点。

13
00:00:35,480 --> 00:00:40,240
But yeah, as you've said, I think it's very much a topic that people can go both ways
但就像你说的，我认为这个话题确实让人们可以

14
00:00:40,240 --> 00:00:41,400
on.
持不同观点。

15
00:00:41,400 --> 00:00:46,420
So why don't we listen to our dialogue as two people discuss animal rights and let's
那我们不如来听听对话，看看两个人如何讨论动物权利，

16
00:00:46,420 --> 00:00:55,320
get their opinions on things.
听听他们的看法。

17
00:00:55,320 --> 00:00:58,040
You should have seen the TV show that was on last night.
你真该看看昨晚的电视节目。

18
00:00:58,040 --> 00:01:00,600
The topic it covered was really interesting.
它讨论的话题非常有趣。

19
00:01:00,600 --> 00:01:01,600
Animal rights.
动物权利。

20
00:01:01,600 --> 00:01:02,920
Do you really believe in that?
你真的相信这个吗？

21
00:01:02,920 --> 00:01:06,760
If they're going to focus on something, they should do it on civil rights.
如果他们要把精力放在某件事上，应该放在民权上。

22
00:01:06,760 --> 00:01:12,200
Yes, but we can't deny that animals are vulnerable, defenseless and are completely at the mercy
是的，但我们不能否认动物是脆弱的、无助的，完全受

23
00:01:12,200 --> 00:01:13,200
of human beings.
人类支配。

24
00:01:13,200 --> 00:01:17,820
I understand your point, but we continue to have transgressions against human rights.
我理解你的观点，但人类权利仍然不断受到侵犯。

25
00:01:17,820 --> 00:01:22,240
If so much attention weren't devoted to the topic of animals, we would then concentrate
如果对动物话题的关注不那么集中，我们就能更专注于

26
00:01:22,240 --> 00:01:25,900
more on saving a human being instead of protecting a koala.
拯救人类，而不是保护一只考拉。

27
00:01:25,900 --> 00:01:27,840
You can't compare apples and oranges.
你不能把苹果和橘子相提并论。

28
00:01:27,840 --> 00:01:31,480
I believe that both topics are important and that we can't ignore them.
我认为这两个话题都很重要，我们不能忽视它们。

29
00:01:31,480 --> 00:01:35,040
The mistreatment of animals can cause a great environmental imbalance.
虐待动物会导致严重的生态失衡。

30
00:01:35,040 --> 00:01:38,440
I believe that governments should prohibit activities like poaching.
我认为政府应该禁止偷猎等活动。

31
00:01:38,440 --> 00:01:40,880
Well, you are right on that point.
嗯，在这一点上你说得对。

32
00:01:40,880 --> 00:01:45,120
This is the reason that I don't buy leather and I try to buy synthetic products.
这就是我不买皮革，尽量买合成产品的原因。

33
00:01:45,120 --> 00:01:46,720
At least you're doing your part.
至少你在尽自己的一份力。

34
00:01:46,720 --> 00:01:50,800
My contribution is to have a pet in the house that I treat like a member of the family.
我的贡献是养了一只宠物，把它当作家人一样对待。

35
00:01:50,800 --> 00:01:54,160
As long as you don't treat it better than your wife, it's fine.
只要你别对它比对你老婆还好，那就没问题。

36
00:01:54,160 --> 00:01:59,640
All right, we're back and both of them have good points, right?
好了，我们回来了，他们两个都有道理，对吧？

37
00:01:59,640 --> 00:02:01,600
In favor and against.
支持和反对的都有。

38
00:02:01,600 --> 00:02:05,760
As you said, they also talk about human rights, which is also a very important topic.
就像你说的，他们也谈到了人权，这也是一个非常重要的话题。

39
00:02:05,760 --> 00:02:10,080
But before we discuss this topic, why don't we take a look at the language that was used
但在我们讨论这个话题之前，不如先来看看

40
00:02:10,080 --> 00:02:13,680
now in Language Takeaway.
语言要点部分用到的语言。

41
00:02:13,680 --> 00:02:14,680
Language Takeaway.
语言要点。

42
00:02:14,680 --> 00:02:19,360
All right, so in Language Takeaway, our first word today is vulnerable.
好的，在语言要点中，我们今天的第一个词是“vulnerable”。

43
00:02:19,360 --> 00:02:21,480
Okay, vulnerable is a great word.
好，“vulnerable”是个很棒的词。

44
00:02:21,480 --> 00:02:22,920
It's a way to describe something.
它是用来描述某事物的形容词。

45
00:02:22,920 --> 00:02:27,720
And so something is vulnerable if it can't really protect itself.
某物如果无法真正保护自己，就是“vulnerable”的。

46
00:02:27,720 --> 00:02:31,040
So you are in danger of being hurt.
所以你处于可能受到伤害的危险中。

47
00:02:31,040 --> 00:02:32,040
Exactly.
没错。

48
00:02:32,040 --> 00:02:33,040
Right.
对。

49
00:02:33,040 --> 00:02:34,040
So you're vulnerable.
所以你是脆弱的。

50
00:02:34,040 --> 00:02:36,400
Now, this isn't only used for animals, right?
这个词不仅仅用于动物，对吧？

51
00:02:36,400 --> 00:02:42,800
It can be like an army is vulnerable if they don't have strong defenses on the borders.
比如，如果一支军队在边境没有强大的防御，它也是脆弱的。

52
00:02:42,800 --> 00:02:43,960
Or my emotions.
或者我的情绪。

53
00:02:43,960 --> 00:02:49,720
I'm feeling vulnerable because I just had a really horrible week and I'm really depressed
我感到脆弱，因为我刚经历了一个非常糟糕的一周，非常沮丧，

54
00:02:49,720 --> 00:02:51,640
and I'm emotionally vulnerable.
情绪上很脆弱。

55
00:02:51,640 --> 00:02:52,920
Okay, very good.
好的，非常好。

56
00:02:52,920 --> 00:02:54,840
So vulnerable.
所以是“vulnerable”。

57
00:02:54,840 --> 00:02:59,000
And they also talked about transgressions against human rights.
他们还谈到了“transgressions against human rights”（对人权的侵犯）。

58
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:00,960
All right, so a transgression is a thing.
好的，“transgression”是一个名词。

59
00:03:00,960 --> 00:03:02,080
It's a noun.
它是名词。

60
00:03:02,080 --> 00:03:09,320
And transgression is like doing something harmful to or against someone or something.
“Transgression”指的是对某人或某物做有害的事情。

61
00:03:09,320 --> 00:03:11,020
So a transgression, it's a noun.
所以“transgression”是名词。

62
00:03:11,020 --> 00:03:13,480
So is it doing something in a bad way?
所以是以不好的方式做事吗？

63
00:03:13,480 --> 00:03:14,480
Exactly.
没错。

64
00:03:14,480 --> 00:03:15,480
It's a bad thing.
是坏事。

65
00:03:15,480 --> 00:03:16,480
It's always negative.
总是负面的。

66
00:03:16,480 --> 00:03:17,480
It's not positive, right?
不是正面的，对吧？

67
00:03:17,480 --> 00:03:18,480
Right.
对。

68
00:03:18,480 --> 00:03:22,160
And so in many prayers, for example, in the Christian faith, you say, you know, Lord,
在很多祈祷中，比如基督教信仰中，你会说：“主啊，

69
00:03:22,160 --> 00:03:26,200
forgive me for my transgressions, for having kind of crossed the line from doing good things
宽恕我的过犯”，意思是跨越了从做好事

70
00:03:26,200 --> 00:03:27,200
to bad things.
到做坏事的界限。

71
00:03:27,200 --> 00:03:28,200
So you're doing bad things.
所以你在做坏事。

72
00:03:28,200 --> 00:03:29,200
Very good.
非常好。

73
00:03:29,200 --> 00:03:32,960
So that's a good way of putting it, to cross the line, to kind of go beyond where you should.
所以“跨越界限”是个很好的说法，指超出了你应该的范围。

74
00:03:32,960 --> 00:03:35,320
All right, so transgressions.
好的，所以是“transgressions”。

75
00:03:35,320 --> 00:03:39,560
And now another very serious problem in the world is poaching.
现在世界上另一个非常严重的问题是“poaching”（偷猎）。

76
00:03:39,560 --> 00:03:42,680
That's one of the things that they said they should control, poaching.
这是他们提到应该控制的事情之一，偷猎。

77
00:03:42,680 --> 00:03:46,120
You might have heard this word in a different context because it does have another meaning,
你可能在其他语境中听过这个词，因为它确实有另一个意思，

78
00:03:46,120 --> 00:03:50,440
but I'm just going to explain the one meaning here that we're talking about, which is killing
但我只解释我们这里讨论的这个意思，即杀害

79
00:03:50,440 --> 00:03:55,520
animals, especially for sport or for selling their skins and their furs.
动物，尤其是为了娱乐或出售它们的皮毛。

80
00:03:55,520 --> 00:03:56,520
Right.
对。

81
00:03:56,520 --> 00:03:58,000
So that's poaching.
所以那就是偷猎。

82
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:00,680
What's the difference between poaching and hunting?
偷猎和打猎有什么区别？

83
00:04:00,680 --> 00:04:01,680
Hunting can be legal.
打猎可以是合法的。

84
00:04:01,680 --> 00:04:02,680
Poaching is illegal.
偷猎是非法的。

85
00:04:02,680 --> 00:04:03,680
Okay.
好的。

86
00:04:03,680 --> 00:04:04,680
So that's the main difference.
所以这是主要区别。

87
00:04:04,680 --> 00:04:05,880
Hunting is usually for sport.
打猎通常是为了娱乐。

88
00:04:05,880 --> 00:04:08,800
You hunt either for food or for sport, right?
你打猎要么是为了食物，要么是为了娱乐，对吧？

89
00:04:08,800 --> 00:04:09,920
Legal hunting.
合法打猎。

90
00:04:09,920 --> 00:04:13,840
But poaching is usually you want to sell, like you said, the fur or the skins or something.
但偷猎通常是为了出售，就像你说的，皮毛或兽皮之类的东西。

91
00:04:13,840 --> 00:04:16,680
Or the tusks on rhinos or something like that.
或者犀牛的角之类的。

92
00:04:16,680 --> 00:04:17,680
Exactly.
没错。

93
00:04:17,680 --> 00:04:18,680
All right, so poaching.
好的，所以是“poaching”。

94
00:04:18,680 --> 00:04:21,160
And then they talked about synthetic products.
然后他们谈到了“synthetic products”（合成产品）。

95
00:04:21,160 --> 00:04:23,280
So what is a synthetic product?
那么什么是合成产品？

96
00:04:23,280 --> 00:04:25,740
Well, synthetic product is something that is man-made.
嗯，合成产品是人造的东西。

97
00:04:25,740 --> 00:04:29,560
So it's not natural in that it doesn't come from the earth.
所以它不是天然的，不是来自地球的。

98
00:04:29,560 --> 00:04:36,080
Cotton is a natural product and plastic, for example, is synthetic or another example.
棉花是天然产品，而塑料是合成产品，或者另一个例子。

99
00:04:36,080 --> 00:04:37,080
Or nylon.
或者尼龙。

100
00:04:37,080 --> 00:04:39,480
Nylon is a really good synthetic product.
尼龙是一种非常好的合成产品。

101
00:04:39,480 --> 00:04:44,960
And so people who don't want to use animal products like wool or leather, they prefer
所以不想使用动物产品（如羊毛或皮革）的人，更喜欢

102
00:04:44,960 --> 00:04:47,600
to use synthetic products.
使用合成产品。

103
00:04:47,600 --> 00:04:50,380
And I think maybe you've heard this in clothing.
我想你可能在服装中听过这个词。

104
00:04:50,380 --> 00:04:52,040
It's called synthetic fibers, right?
它被称为合成纤维，对吧？

105
00:04:52,040 --> 00:04:53,760
Like nylon or polyester.
比如尼龙或聚酯纤维。

106
00:04:53,760 --> 00:04:54,760
Exactly.
没错。

107
00:04:54,760 --> 00:04:57,140
These are all the words that we have for language takeaway today.
这些就是我们今天语言要点中的所有词汇。

108
00:04:57,140 --> 00:05:01,680
So why don't we move on now to a couple of very interesting phrases that we saw in the
那我们接下来看看对话中出现的几个非常有趣的短语，

109
00:05:01,680 --> 00:05:05,480
dialogue now in Fluency Builder.
在流利度构建部分。

110
00:05:05,480 --> 00:05:06,480
Fluency Builder.
流利度构建。

111
00:05:06,480 --> 00:05:12,480
Okay, this first phrase is, well, it's a common one, but it's definitely not used in very
好的，第一个短语是，嗯，很常见，但绝对不是在

112
00:05:12,480 --> 00:05:13,960
happy circumstances.
愉快的场合使用的。

113
00:05:13,960 --> 00:05:18,440
We say that something or someone is at the mercy of someone else.
我们说某物或某人“at the mercy of”（受……支配）另一个人。

114
00:05:18,440 --> 00:05:22,400
Okay, so animals are at the mercy of human beings.
好的，所以动物受人类支配。

115
00:05:22,400 --> 00:05:23,680
What does this mean exactly?
这到底是什么意思？

116
00:05:23,680 --> 00:05:24,680
Mercy?
“Mercy”？

117
00:05:24,680 --> 00:05:29,880
So basically, it means that the animals, in this case, don't have control of what's going
基本上，这意味着动物在这种情况下无法控制

118
00:05:29,880 --> 00:05:30,880
on.
发生的事情。

119
00:05:30,880 --> 00:05:33,680
So human beings are the ones that control everything.
所以人类是掌控一切的一方。

120
00:05:33,680 --> 00:05:40,720
So if I decide to kill them, then they are at my mercy, at my will, at my whim.
所以如果我决定杀死它们，它们就受我的支配，听凭我的意愿和一时兴起。

121
00:05:40,720 --> 00:05:41,720
Exactly.
没错。

122
00:05:41,720 --> 00:05:45,840
And so you could say, I'm at your mercy, Marco, please just like help me out with this.
所以你可以说，我全听你的了，Marco，请帮帮我吧。

123
00:05:45,840 --> 00:05:47,160
It's like you're the one in control.
就好像你是掌控局面的人。

124
00:05:47,160 --> 00:05:49,320
You're the one who can help the situation.
你是那个能帮忙解决问题的人。

125
00:05:49,320 --> 00:05:50,320
Will you help?
你会帮忙吗？

126
00:05:50,320 --> 00:05:51,320
Exactly.
没错。

127
00:05:51,320 --> 00:05:53,600
I'm at the mercy of someone.
我受制于某人。

128
00:05:53,600 --> 00:05:59,320
And then they were talking and debating this thing and an interesting comparison came up.
然后他们讨论这件事时，出现了一个有趣的比较。

129
00:05:59,320 --> 00:06:01,640
You can't compare apples and oranges.
你不能把苹果和橘子相提并论。

130
00:06:01,640 --> 00:06:04,440
All right, you're going to hear this all the time in English.
好了，你在英语中会经常听到这个说法。

131
00:06:04,440 --> 00:06:07,480
It's not just a funny little phrase that the person uses.
这不仅仅是一个有趣的小短语。

132
00:06:07,480 --> 00:06:09,240
It's a very common idiom.
这是一个非常常见的习语。

133
00:06:09,240 --> 00:06:14,440
And so we say, it's like apples and oranges or you can't compare apples and oranges.
所以我们说，这就像苹果和橘子，或者你不能把苹果和橘子相提并论。

134
00:06:14,440 --> 00:06:18,880
And this is essentially saying, these are two different things.
这基本上就是说，这是两件不同的事。

135
00:06:18,880 --> 00:06:19,880
Completely different.
完全不同。

136
00:06:19,880 --> 00:06:20,880
Completely different.
完全不同。

137
00:06:20,880 --> 00:06:24,320
So I can't compare him and her because it's apples and oranges.
所以我不能拿他和她比较，因为这是苹果和橘子。

138
00:06:24,320 --> 00:06:26,320
They're two different things, two different people.
他们是两件不同的事，两个不同的人。

139
00:06:26,320 --> 00:06:27,320
Right.
对。

140
00:06:27,320 --> 00:06:29,760
Because that's what in the movie, you said they were like peas and carrots.
因为在电影里，你说他们就像豌豆和胡萝卜。

141
00:06:29,760 --> 00:06:30,760
They just go together well.
他们就是很搭配。

142
00:06:30,760 --> 00:06:31,760
They just go together.
他们就是很合得来。

143
00:06:31,760 --> 00:06:32,760
Does that make sense?
这说得通吗？

144
00:06:32,760 --> 00:06:33,760
Not really.
不太说得通。

145
00:06:33,760 --> 00:06:35,360
Forrest Gump was a little bit strange like that.
《阿甘正传》有点奇怪，就像那样。

146
00:06:35,360 --> 00:06:40,000
But I think the meaning is that if I say that's a big apple and I say that's a small
但我觉得意思是，如果我说那是个大苹果，而我说那是个小苹果，

147
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:42,600
apple, they're all apples so I can compare them.
它们都是苹果，所以我可以比较。

148
00:06:42,600 --> 00:06:45,600
But I say this is a really big orange and that's a really big apple.
但我说这是个很大的橘子，那是个很大的苹果。

149
00:06:45,600 --> 00:06:47,880
Well, they're different.
嗯，它们不同。

150
00:06:47,880 --> 00:06:49,880
You just can't compare them.
你就是没法比较。

151
00:06:49,880 --> 00:06:51,320
All right.
好了。

152
00:06:51,320 --> 00:06:56,360
And towards the end, the person said that you're doing your part.
在最后，那个人说你在尽自己的一份力。

153
00:06:56,360 --> 00:06:57,360
You're doing your part.
你在尽自己的一份力。

154
00:06:57,360 --> 00:07:01,960
Yeah, so this is a hard one to understand sometimes because it's not like a part in
是啊，这有时很难理解，因为它不像戏剧里的角色。

155
00:07:01,960 --> 00:07:02,960
a play.
它更像是社会中的一部分。

156
00:07:02,960 --> 00:07:04,280
It's more like a part in society.
你在帮助让社会、文化或文明变得更好。

157
00:07:04,280 --> 00:07:09,080
You're helping make society or culture or civilization better.
所以你在做贡献。

158
00:07:09,080 --> 00:07:10,560
So you're contributing.
没错。

159
00:07:10,560 --> 00:07:11,560
Exactly.
没错。

160
00:07:11,560 --> 00:07:17,640
So for example, what would be an example of a person doing their part towards society?
那么举个例子，一个人为社会尽自己的一份力是什么样的？

161
00:07:17,640 --> 00:07:20,200
Well, for example, I don't own a car.
嗯，比如，我没有车。

162
00:07:20,200 --> 00:07:24,440
I ride my bike and it's my way of doing my part to help the environment.
我骑自行车，这是我尽自己的一份力来帮助环境的方式。

163
00:07:24,440 --> 00:07:25,600
Okay, very good.
好的，非常好。

164
00:07:25,600 --> 00:07:31,520
So I can't, obviously, I can't buy a factory that's very green or I can't do all these
所以我不能，显然，我不能买一个非常环保的工厂，也不能做所有这些

165
00:07:31,520 --> 00:07:32,520
things to change the world.
改变世界的事情。

166
00:07:32,520 --> 00:07:36,640
So I'm going to do small things that those are my way of doing my part.
所以我会做小事，这些是我尽自己一份力的方式。

167
00:07:36,640 --> 00:07:37,640
Okay.
好的。

168
00:07:37,640 --> 00:07:39,440
So like another example would be recycling.
所以另一个例子是回收利用。

169
00:07:39,440 --> 00:07:40,440
That's doing your part.
那就是尽自己的一份力。

170
00:07:40,440 --> 00:07:41,440
Exactly.
没错。

171
00:07:41,440 --> 00:07:47,080
Or in this case, the person bought only synthetic products, nothing made from nature.
或者在这个例子中，那个人只买合成产品，不买任何天然制品。

172
00:07:47,080 --> 00:07:48,840
All right, very good.
好的，非常好。

173
00:07:48,840 --> 00:07:51,200
So very interesting phrases.
所以是非常有趣的短语。

174
00:07:51,200 --> 00:08:02,600
Why don't we listen to our dialogue for the last time and then we'll be right back.
我们最后再听一遍对话，然后马上回来。

175
00:08:02,600 --> 00:08:05,320
You should have seen the TV show that was on last night.
你应该看看昨晚的电视节目。

176
00:08:05,320 --> 00:08:07,880
The topic it covered was really interesting.
它涵盖的话题真的很有趣。

177
00:08:07,880 --> 00:08:08,880
Animal rights.
动物权利。

178
00:08:08,880 --> 00:08:10,240
Do you really believe in that?
你真的相信那个吗？

179
00:08:10,240 --> 00:08:14,040
If they're going to focus on something, they should do it on civil rights.
如果他们要把重点放在某件事上，应该放在民权上。

180
00:08:14,040 --> 00:08:19,480
Yes, but we can't deny that animals are vulnerable, defenseless, and are completely at the mercy
是的，但我们不能否认动物是脆弱的、无助的，完全受制于

181
00:08:19,480 --> 00:08:20,680
of human beings.
人类。

182
00:08:20,680 --> 00:08:25,120
I understand your point, but we continue to have transgressions against human rights.
我理解你的观点，但我们仍然有侵犯人权的行为。

183
00:08:25,120 --> 00:08:29,560
If so much attention weren't devoted to the topic of animals, we would then concentrate
如果对动物话题的关注不那么集中，我们就会更专注于拯救人类，

184
00:08:29,560 --> 00:08:33,200
more on saving a human being instead of protecting a koala.
而不是保护一只考拉。

185
00:08:33,200 --> 00:08:35,160
You can't compare apples and oranges.
你不能把苹果和橘子相提并论。

186
00:08:35,160 --> 00:08:38,800
I believe that both topics are important and that we can't ignore them.
我相信这两个话题都很重要，我们不能忽视它们。

187
00:08:38,800 --> 00:08:42,360
The mistreatment of animals can cause a great environmental imbalance.
虐待动物会导致严重的环境失衡。

188
00:08:42,360 --> 00:08:45,760
I believe that governments should prohibit activities like poaching.
我认为政府应该禁止偷猎等活动。

189
00:08:45,760 --> 00:08:48,200
Well, you are right on that point.
嗯，在那一点上你是对的。

190
00:08:48,200 --> 00:08:52,440
This is the reason that I don't buy leather and I try to buy synthetic products.
这就是我不买皮革，并尽量买合成产品的原因。

191
00:08:52,440 --> 00:08:54,040
At least you're doing your part.
至少你在尽自己的一份力。

192
00:08:54,040 --> 00:08:58,120
My contribution is to have a pet in the house that I treat like a member of the family.
我的贡献是在家里养一只宠物，我把它当作家庭成员对待。

193
00:08:58,120 --> 00:09:01,440
As long as you don't treat it better than your wife, it's fine.
只要你别对它比对你老婆还好，那就没问题。

194
00:09:01,440 --> 00:09:09,040
All right, so a debatable topic, animals and animal rights.
好了，一个值得辩论的话题，动物和动物权利。

195
00:09:09,040 --> 00:09:10,040
What do you think?
你怎么看？

196
00:09:10,040 --> 00:09:11,440
Well, I'll say this.
嗯，我要说这个。

197
00:09:11,440 --> 00:09:17,600
I would be a hypocrite if I said that it's bad to hurt animals because I'm a meat eater.
如果我说伤害动物不好，那我就是个伪君子，因为我吃肉。

198
00:09:17,600 --> 00:09:20,520
I like to eat meat and I like to wear leather.
我喜欢吃肉，也喜欢穿皮革。

199
00:09:20,520 --> 00:09:23,240
But I do think it's bad to mistreat animals.
但我确实认为虐待动物不好。

200
00:09:23,240 --> 00:09:30,120
So I try to buy free-range chicken or meat from places I know that treat the animals
所以我尽量买散养鸡或来自我知道善待动物的地方的肉，

201
00:09:30,120 --> 00:09:36,040
well and I definitely disagree with poaching and with using animals, especially endangered
而且我坚决反对偷猎和利用动物，尤其是濒危动物

202
00:09:36,040 --> 00:09:39,880
animals for money and cash purposes.
来赚钱。

203
00:09:39,880 --> 00:09:41,520
And so that's my position.
这就是我的立场。

204
00:09:41,520 --> 00:09:42,520
But what's yours?
但你的立场呢？

205
00:09:42,520 --> 00:09:44,080
I mean, I know you eat meat too.
我的意思是，我知道你也吃肉。

206
00:09:44,080 --> 00:09:45,360
No, yeah, of course.
不，是的，当然。

207
00:09:45,360 --> 00:09:51,720
And I think even though protection of animals is a very important topic and you don't want
而且我认为，尽管保护动物是一个非常重要的话题，你不想

208
00:09:51,720 --> 00:09:56,480
the mistreatment of these little creatures that are very vulnerable to us because we're
虐待这些对我们来说非常脆弱的小生物，因为我们

209
00:09:56,480 --> 00:09:59,240
smarter than them in the end.
最终比它们聪明。

210
00:09:59,240 --> 00:10:05,760
But I think also it has to do a lot with superstition sometimes and kind of mystical and magical
但我也认为这有时与迷信以及某种神秘和神奇

211
00:10:05,760 --> 00:10:06,760
things.
的事情有很大关系。

212
00:10:06,760 --> 00:10:11,520
For example, people killing rhinos because they believe that the rhino horn has amazing
例如，人们杀死犀牛，因为他们相信犀牛角有神奇的

213
00:10:11,520 --> 00:10:16,360
curing properties or the same thing with elephant tusks and stuff like that.
疗效，或者象牙之类的东西也一样。

214
00:10:16,360 --> 00:10:21,920
So it also involves this certain aspect that people almost don't know any better.
所以这也涉及到一个方面，即人们几乎不知道更好的做法。

215
00:10:21,920 --> 00:10:25,760
They just truly believe that these things actually work or that they will help them.
他们只是真心相信这些东西真的有效，或者会帮助他们。

216
00:10:25,760 --> 00:10:30,680
So they don't consider the, like in the dialogue said, the imbalance that they create in the
所以他们不考虑，就像对话中说的，他们在环境中造成的

217
00:10:30,680 --> 00:10:33,400
environment or the consequences.
失衡或后果。

218
00:10:33,400 --> 00:10:37,960
Or there might be some very serious evolutionary consequences that we cannot even imagine.
或者可能会有一些我们甚至无法想象的非常严重的进化后果。

219
00:10:37,960 --> 00:10:43,200
And so, you know, things change kind of over time, sometimes quickly and sometimes slowly.
所以，你知道，事情会随着时间的推移而变化，有时快，有时慢。

220
00:10:43,200 --> 00:10:47,640
But if we force change really quickly, who knows what the results are going to be.
但如果我们强行快速改变，谁知道结果会是什么。

221
00:10:47,640 --> 00:10:49,200
It might be really negative for us.
可能对我们非常不利。

222
00:10:49,200 --> 00:10:50,200
Exactly.
没错。

223
00:10:50,200 --> 00:10:51,320
And that's what we want to know now.
这就是我们现在想知道的。

224
00:10:51,320 --> 00:10:54,240
What do you think about these topics?
你对这些话题怎么看？

225
00:10:54,240 --> 00:10:58,000
Because in the end, the environment, animals, they're all connected.
因为最终，环境、动物，它们都是相互关联的。

226
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:05,040
If you wipe out all the foxes in a forest, then you're going to have too many snakes
如果你消灭了森林里所有的狐狸，那么你就会有太多蛇

227
00:11:05,040 --> 00:11:06,360
running around, right?
到处乱跑，对吧？

228
00:11:06,360 --> 00:11:07,600
So what do you think?
所以你怎么看？

